            {
                "s2_paper_id": "749d55cd1a30ad55c8208e650d5bdddea24fdd46",
                "title": "We need better and more PopSci by scientists.",
                "year": 2024,
                "venue": "Science",
                "citation_count": 1,
                "reference_count": 0,
                "abstract": "Any scientist knows that to be a good scientist, they must conduct thoughtful research; generate high-quality, verifiable results and analyses; and get them into circulation in the scientific community. However, what often goes underappreciated is that this good science will likely remain ignored by most of the world if one doesn't find a way to get it out beyond the scientific community. Unfortunately, when it comes to making our science accessible, we scientists all too often fall short. And that's when the nonscientist public turn to other nonscientists they can understand. Hence, we find ourselves in a world shaped by a lot of misguided, and often erroneous, information about science.",
                "authors": [
                    {
                        "s2_author_id": "2253746402",
                        "name": "Agust\u00edn Fuentes"
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "s2_paper_id": "1125dd62b757ed4a6c22a48f12b60ada0cf98136",
                "title": "Humans are biocultural, science should be too.",
                "year": 2023,
                "venue": "Science",
                "citation_count": 6,
                "reference_count": 0,
                "abstract": "COVID-19 is restructuring societies. Loneliness is a global health threat. Large language models are outputting biased health care information, and human-artificial intelligence (AI) interfaces are reshaping how we live. For most humans, technology, biology, and society are hopelessly entangled. Are the sciences prepared to tackle the contemporary human experience?",
                "authors": [
                    {
                        "s2_author_id": "2253746402",
                        "name": "Agust\u00edn Fuentes"
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "s2_paper_id": "af8232666a8b268ed8bef8d61e72ec959bfa709a",
                "title": "Steps towards a more holistic, dynamic and integrative approach to the evolution of religious systems",
                "year": 2023,
                "venue": "Religion, Brain &amp; Behavior",
                "citation_count": 0,
                "reference_count": 19,
                "abstract": "Formal, large-scale religions and religious institutions\u2014such as Christianity, Hinduism, Buddhism and Islam\u2014have roots going back no more 4000\u20138000 years (Bella, 2011). Our distinctively human lineage (the genus Homo ) is more than two million years old and our species ( Homo sapiens ) emerged something like 300,000 years ago (Galway-Witham et al., 2019). Religion as we know it is very recent, and we, as a species, are not. This is a challenge to the reconstruction of the evolutionary pathways for religion and the modeling of the evolutionary processes that facilitate the emergence, and maintenance, of religious capacities, and religions themselves. For the vast majority of human history, we have little material evidence representing the eight building blocks of religious systems outlined by Purzycki and Sosis (2022, pp. 142\u2013146): ritual, taboo, authority, myth, sacred, supernatural agent, moral obligation, and meaning. Thus, studying religion in an evolutionary sense offers a particular set of challenges: how and why did such a dynamic emerge and why is it so pervasive in contemporary humanity? In this book, Ben Purzycki and Rich Sosis 1 offer some-thing a bit different from the majority of evolutionary models for religion: they argue for envisioning religion and religious processes in the context of a dynamic adaptive systems framework. Purzycki and Sosis argue that \u201creligion is an adaptation that exists within, between and beyond individuals\u201d (2022, p. 11). In doing so they push against a range of overly reductive models and approaches and offer a more comprehensive and culturally, ethnographically, and ecologically contextualized approach. This frame stands somewhat in contrast to much of what currently exists in the cognitive science of, and evolutionary explanations for, religion. This adaptive systems approach, while maintaining a core functionalist frame (e.g., explaining what religion is \u201cfor\u201d in an evolutionary sense), highlights the flexibility and adaptability of religious systems, noting how",
                "authors": [
                    {
                        "s2_author_id": "2253746402",
                        "name": "Agust\u00edn Fuentes"
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "s2_paper_id": "cd8b394536d87f3098b52e265c89a5066df4dace",
                "title": "Environmental violence: a tool for planetary health research.",
                "year": 2023,
                "venue": "Lancet Planetary Health",
                "citation_count": 2,
                "reference_count": 110,
                "abstract": null,
                "authors": [
                    {
                        "s2_author_id": "97212453",
                        "name": "Richard A. Marcantonio"
                    },
